narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: Yes, great class to learn about math
Yeah- pretty light workload and not too taxing.
Only if you have a burning love of history of math...I thought I did but my flame has been dampened a little since this class

I would recommend this class if you're willing to push yourself to do the reading and have good discussions. Professor Summers is one of the smartest people living and contributes massive amounts to every discussion, but there are lulls in the discussion sometimes that necessitate students stepping up. Still, it's a very interesting class, especially if you're a math-inclined person. Especially math- or science-inclined people should also note that non-QR people in the class frequently say double- or triple-take-worthy quotables reflecting a strange understanding of real-world phenomena.
I would recommend it... but tentatively. Shop it and see if you like bill summers as a teacher cause his style of seminars is kind of different

This course is a great opportunity to read the original words of some of historys greatest mathematicians. If youre interested in mathematics and/or philosophy, the syllabus is reason enough to take the class. The workload is very light, however (a final paper and presentation), so you need to be self-motivated to get a lot out of the readings. I would recommend this course to anyone whos curious to know how math has evolved from Euclid up through modern computer science.
Not really, unless you have a paper topic in mind already.
I definitely would if you are interested in philosophy, history of science or intellectual history.
